as soon as he said about the birds i must admit i hadn't thought about it before, so I googled it 'Wind turbines kill an estimated 140,000 to 328,000 birds each year in North America,(that's just one country!!!) making it the most threatening form of green energy. And yet, it's also one of the most rapidly expanding energy industries: more than 49,000 individual wind turbines now exist across 39 states.'

So what I would have liked to have seen was a little bit more of a solution brought forth.
If he'd gone on to explain an even safer form of sustainable energy then that would have be constructive.

But then again this clip is shown out of context I guess for a reason, to get people upset. No idea what led him to making this point, and I hate it when people just take a small portion of what is said, because he could have gone on to provide a solution but we'll never know unless we go looking for the full clip, which who has time for that?!

I think this is more a testimony to media manipulation being an issue here. its a click bait so that people spend 3 minutes becoming frustrated and pop off without first taking a moment to have a little nose at multiple sources and make there own minds up.

Let's face it, if a respected person would have said this then people would be more recpetive to it.
You guys seeing how this game is played yet? 😉😅👌🏼

snippet.textDisplay:
I see he doesn't mention the many millions of telephone poles, electric pylons, miles and miles of cables, huge mobile phone towers, and ever-expanding roads that spoil landscapes much more than turbines.


Ahem. Windmills have 30 year lifespan, not 10.


As for that nonsense about birds. I used to live very close to a wind turbine (now 20 years old, to prove the above claim) and never ever saw one dead bird underneath.
Considering birds have to negotiate a space shared by a lot of other flying birds, land with excellent accuracy in trees, and Birds of Prey hunt on the wing with great success, I think that is sufficient proof that they are not so stupid as to fly smack-bang into a slow moving turbine blade that can be seen for miles.


And what the heck is he talking about fumes for? I think he's getting confused with coal plants there.
